Let me analyze the mutation more carefully.

Original: `if (chunk.lastIndexOf('\n') === -1) return;`
Mutated: `if (false) return;`

The original returns early (skipping the split/process logic) when a chunk has no newline. The mutated version never returns early.

The key behavioral difference: when a chunk has NO newline, the original skips `buffer.split('\n')` processing. The mutated version proceeds to split and process. 

When there's no newline in the chunk, `buffer.split('\n')` returns `[buffer]`, then `arr.pop()` sets `buffer = arr[0]` (the whole buffer) and `arr` becomes empty. So `arr.forEach` does nothing. This seems equivalent...

BUT wait - `buffer += chunk` happens BEFORE the check. If the original returns early after `buffer += chunk`, buffer grows. If mutated continues, it splits, pops last element back to buffer... 

Actually the critical difference: the mutated code processes `buffer` contents even when chunk has no newline. If `buffer` already contains a complete row (with `\n` from a previous chunk), the mutated version would process it prematurely while the original would wait. This could cause the `end` handler to see a non-empty buffer and emit an error about corrupted data.

